value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of wax, which includes C16 and C18 fatty acids.
The process in which a relatively unspecialized epidermal cell acquires the specialized features of a trichome cell. An example of this process is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the thylakoid membrane.

definition.value: See also the cellular component term 'thylakoid membrane ; GO:0042651'.

value.value: A cyclic series of interconversions involving three xanthophylls, violoxanthin, antheraxanthin, and zeaxanthin. The xanthophyll cycle is involved in regulating energy dissipation in light harvesting complex II.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of seed germination.
Any process that activates or increase the rate of seed germination.
The organismal movement by which the tip of a plant organ follows a spiral pattern as a consequence of growth.
Compaction of chromatin structure prior to meiosis in eukaryotic cells.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an acetate stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a boron-containing substance stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a carbon dioxide (CO2) stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a metal ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an iron ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an iron(II) ion stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an iron(III) ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a manganese ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a zinc ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an aluminum ion stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nickel cation stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mycotoxin stimulus. A mycotoxin is a toxic chemical substance produced by fungi.
The process leading to the spontaneous opening of the fruit permitting the escape of seeds.
The process of thermal induction in plants in which flowering is promoted by exposure to low temperatures.
The process in which a plant acquires the ability to respond to a floral inductive signal.
Any process involved in the transition of a plant from a juvenile phase of vegetative development to an adult phase of vegetative development.
The regionalization process that gives rise to the patterning of the conducting tissues. An example of this process is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The process in which a guard mother cell acquires the specialized features of a guard cell.
The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell in the root epidermis acquires the specialized features of a trichoblast or atrichoblast.
The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a trichoblast, a root epidermal cell that will give rise to a root hair.
The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an atrichoblast, a root epidermal cell that will not give rise to a root hair.
The process involved in the specification of an atrichoblast.
The process involved in the specification of a trichoblast.
Any process that modulates atrichoblast fate specification.

label.value: positive regulation of atrichoblast fate specification

value.value: Any process that induces or promotes atrichoblast fate specification.

label.value: negative regulation of atrichoblast fate specification

value.value: Any process that suppresses atrichoblast fate specification.
Any process that modulates trichoblast fate specification.

label.value: negative regulation of trichoblast fate specification

value.value: Any process that suppresses trichoblast fate specification.

label.value: positive regulation of trichoblast fate specification

value.value: Any process that induces or promotes trichoblast fate specification.
The process in which the anatomical structures of embryonic shoot are generated and organized.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the primary meristem over time, from formation to the mature structure, as it occurs during plant embryogenesis. The primary meristem tissue is the protoderm, ground meristem and procambium.
The formation of the primary meristem or meristematic tissue that gives rise to the ground tissues.
The formation of the primary meristem or meristematic tissue that gives rise to the primary vascular tissue.
The formation of the primary meristem or meristematic tissue that gives rise to the epidermis.

label.value: zygote asymmetric cytokinesis in embryo sac

value.value: The division of the zygote in a plane perpendicular to the long axis of the embryo sac to produce a larger basal cell near the micropyle and a small terminal cell close to what was the central cell and is now the developing endosperm. An example of this process is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The division of the zygote into two daughter cells that will adopt developmentally distinct potentials.
The specification of a meristem which will give rise to a primary or lateral root.
The specification of the meristem which will give rise to all post-embryonic above-ground structures of the plant as well as the non-root below-ground structures, such as rhizomes and tubers.
Any process involved in maintaining the identity, size and shape of a meristem.
The process in which an organism retains a population of meristem cells, preventing the commitment of all stem cell progeny to a differentiated cell fate.
Any process involved in maintaining the size and shape of a meristem.
The process in which an organism retains a population of floral meristem cells, preventing the commitment of all stem cell progeny to a differentiated cell fate.
